A large part of me has often feared that someday, my mind will slowly leave me too. I think I will cry when details or memories don‚Äôt come back to me. I keep somewhat of a rolling diary of my core memories that starts at approximately age 4
& I wish we knew more about our minds.

My dad no longer wants to discuss intricacies, regardless of context. Things were well researched before & don‚Äôt need to be deliberated upon. He is kind-hearted but will be stuck with many of his ways from now on. I pray his impulsiveness will never lead to anything more.

I was often a far better caregiver for those who reminded me of family due to the conditions they were afflicted with. I watched my dad, who was often brutish & rash, exhibit his most compassionate behavior taking care of his ailing dad, tending to him like a father w/ a baby.

After HS I was a CNA. There are many times I regret leaving healthcare for fear I wouldn‚Äôt get into med school. I loved patients w/ Alzheimer‚Äôs the most. Their nighttime confusion could lead to violent behavior but more often it led to humorous situations. My heart bled for them.

Cognitive changes are complicated & conditions like dementia frighten & fascinate me. 2/5 siblings (including my grandpa) had Alzheimer‚Äôs & Parkinson‚Äôs on his side. It‚Äôs heartbreaking to see some of the world‚Äôs most brilliant people slowly succumb to injuries of their own mind.

My brother & I were ribbing my dad at Christmas for continually passing good cards in a game where Aces alternate each round. He pulled me aside after & mentioned the stroke for the first time since last summer. I wasn‚Äôt teasing that hard but it clearly hit a button for him.

I‚Äôve spent too much time thinking about aging, death & dying for far too long since I watched a human pass for the first time at the age of 9. But it never slows down. He‚Äôs 68 & has a good 20 years left with his good physical health‚Ä¶ but where the mind leads, you never know.

My dad had a mild stroke last summer & luckily regained his health quick & hasn‚Äôt had any movement issues. But he already worried me before w/ Alzheimer‚Äôs symptoms. Spending 2 weeks at home & repeating simple but key details has made me realize some things just won‚Äôt be the same.
